Date: Wed, 02 Jan 2019 09:45:18 +0000

NEW YORK 
Wednesday, January 2, 2019 G Follow Law360 
Top New York Cases To Watch In 2019 
Big cases often find their homes in New York, and the coming year will be no 
different. President Donald Trump's campaign-season and charitable conduct 
have come under legal assault, former Hollywood kingpin Harvey Weinstein 
faces sexual assault charges and alleged systemic corruption in college 
basketball will go before a jury. Here, Law360 provides a rundown of some 
Empire State cases attorneys will be closely watching in 2019. Read full 
article » 
Financial Services Litigation To Watch In 2019 
On the horizon for the financial services industry in the new year are cases 
that will turn up the heat on the debate over the Consumer Financial 
Protection Bureau's constitutionality, test the legality of the much-vaunted 
fintech banking charter and potentially increase the number of lawsuits from 
homeowners fighting foreclosure. Here, Law360 examines the cases that 
experts most often singled out for their potential impact on the industry. Read 
full article 
» 
NYC Real Estate Legislation, Regulation To Watch In 2019 
Rezoning in various neighborhoods and the question of short-term rentals 
are among the areas of regulation and legislation that real estate lawyers in 
New York will be watching in 2019. Read full article » 
Sports Cases To Watch In 2019 
After 2018 brought an end to some major long-standing legal disputes in 
sports, such as a U.S. Supreme Court ruling that opened the door for sports 
betting, the new year is set to see more developments and potential 
resolutions to many other significant sports legal cases. Here, Law360 takes 
a look at sports law cases attorneys to watch in 2019. Read full article 
EXPERT ANALYSIS 
3 Key Food And Beverage Trends To Watch In 2019 
As we ring in the new year, attorneys with Alston & Bird LLP discuss what to 
expect from slack-fill litigation, partially hydrogenated oil-related lawsuits, and 
the messy regulatory landscape of cannabidiol and THC edibles. Read full 
article » 
Why More Law Firms Will Embrace Remote Work In 2019 
Leveraging technology in a fiercely competitive market is a key factor driving 
law firms toward technology adoption in 2019, as they face growing demand 
from legal talent and clients for the ability to connect, access and control 
information whenever and wherever needed, says Tomas Suros of tech 
provider AbacusNext. Read full article »

LEGAL INDUSTRY 
3 Worries Keeping Managing Partners Up At Night In 2019 
Going into 2019, managing partners have a lot on their plates. Here, Law360 
takes an in-depth dive into the three things that are worrying managing 
partners most in 2019. Read full 
article » 
Law Firms Likely To Keep Expanding Parental Benefits In 2019 
Many law firms revamped their parental benefits policies in 2018, making 
attorneys and staff eligible for more paid leave and moving away from 
offering different benefits for different genders. Here's a look back at the firms 
that made waves, and a preview of what we might see in the coming year. 
Read full article » 
The 3 Hottest Practice Areas For 2019 
A strong, although uncertain, economy going into the new year is driving an 
uptick in work for law firms as corporations scramble to position themselves 
for success in 2019, creating particularly heavy demand for attorneys in three 
key practice areas. Read 
full article » 
Where Lateral Hiring Will Be Most Active In 2019 
Buoyed by a strong economy and expectations of continued growth in 
demand, the increasingly dynamic lateral market shows no signs of slowing 
in 2019, with some regions more primed for activity than others, according to 
multiple recruiters and industry reports. Read full 
article » 
How #MeToo Will Keep Shaping The Legal Industry 
In its first year, the #MeToo movement had a profound impact on almost 
every industry and level of the culture, including the legal sector, where law 
firms and federal courts were forced to reckon with policies and practices that 
allowed workplace harassment to go unaddressed for years. Here, Law360 
takes a look at some of the ways the #MeToo movement will continue to 
shape the legal industry in 2019 as it enters its second year. Read full article 
4 Worries That Will Keep GCs Awake At Night In 2019 
As general counsels across industries plan for the new year, they expect the 
increasing occurrence of cyberthreats and emerging technologies to be 
among the most pressing issues that will lead to many sleepless nights in the 
months ahead. Here, Law360 looks at the primary concerns worrying in-
house leaders. Read full 
article » 
The Factors Shaping General Counsel Pay In 2019 
The total amount reflected in many general counsel paychecks has climbed 
in recent years thanks to complex regulatory environments and the evolving 
role of the top corporate lawyer, and that trend is only expected to continue in 
2019. Read full article » 
'Leapfrogging' Trump Appeals Jolt Sleepy Supreme Court 
The Supreme Court's relatively quiet term is being rocked by the Trump 
administration's emergency appeals over controversial policies on 
immigration and transgender service members, thrusting the high court once 
more into the national spotlight. Read full article » 
Podcast 
Law360's Pro Say: The Biggest Legal Stories Of 2018 
For the final episode of Law360's Pro Say podcast in 2018, we're taking a 
look back at three of the biggest legal stories of the year, including Justice 
Brett Kavanaugh's nomination to the U.S. Supreme Court and the sexual 
assault allegations that followed, immigration policy turmoil around the 
separation of children from their families at the border, and the criminal
